                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4502a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-06-23T16:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 23, 1922—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>153. Japanese Chargé d’Affaires in a public address recently delivered at
                    Baltimore referred to the withdrawal of the Japanese troops from Hankow, and
                    stated that the Japanese Government “hopes that all the other foreign troops
                    stationed in Peking and other places according to the protocol signed after the
                    Boxer rebellion of 1900<note n="54" xml:id="d484fn54">For final protocol, signed
                        Sept. 7, 1901, see <ref target="frus1901China#pg_306">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1901, app. (Affairs in China),
                            p. 306</ref>.</note> will also be withdrawn as soon as order is restored
                    in China. The Japanese Minister at Peking has already been instructed <pb
                        facs="0841" n="721" xml:id="pg_721"/> to take up this matter with the
                    representatives of the Powers there”.</p>
                <p>The Department desires information as to whether you or your interested
                    colleagues have been approached on this matter by the Japanese Minister.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Tokyo as No. 60 for information only.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
